 a new direction of political thought using the concept of the everyday: Following Henri Lefebvre, Agnes Heller, and Lawrence Grossberg, she outlines a complex theory of everyday life which allows the perception of the everyday as an ambivalent political battleground between domination and resistance, providing the starting point for a practical theory of politics beyond the state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aFeminismus. 4aMacht. 4aPolitik. 4aPolitikwissenschaft. 4aPolitische Philosophie. 4aPolitische Soziologie. 4aPolitische Theorie. 4aPoststrukturalismus. 4aPrivatheit. 4aÖffentlichkeit. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aPolitical Philosophy.  aPolitical Science.  aPolitical Sociology.  aPolitical Theory.  aPost-structuralism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2016z978311070100508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPP Plus eBook-Package 2016z97831107010120 cprintz978383762539440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783839425398?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783839425398zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783839425398/original  a978-3-11-070100-5 DG Plus eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-070101-2 PP Plus eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA